{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XeTZW5i1Y3Rn621YoZFExQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is clear: `es-cluster-0` is trying to resolve `es-cluster-1.es-cluster` and `es-cluster-2.es-cluster` in its discovery configuration, but those DNS entries don't exist anymore. The `initial_master_nodes` configuration includes all 3 nodes, and the discovery is failing because it needs a quorum.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully - this is ES 7.17.9. In ES 7.x, the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting is only used for initial cluster bootstrapping (first startup). After that, the cluster uses the committed cluster state.\nThe real problem is that when two of the three master-eligible nodes disappear, the remaining node can't achieve the quorum it needs to form a cluster. The discovery warnings about unresolved hosts are just noise - the actual blocker is that with 3 master nodes originally, you need 2 for quorum, so a single node can't proceed. I need to reconfigure the voting configuration to fix this in ES 7.x.\n\nI can use the Voting Configuration Exclusions API to tell the cluster that the removed nodes should be excluded from voting, which would let the remaining node form a quorum on its own. The challenge is that the cluster is currently showing a 503 error because no master has been discovered - but I'm wondering if the voting configuration API might still be callable locally on the node itself, since it modifies local state rather than requiring cluster consensus.\n\nLet me think through the Elasticsearch 7.x discovery process more carefully. The `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting only applies during initial bootstrap, and after that the voting configuration is stored in the cluster state and persisted to disk. When scaling down to a single node, that node needs to reconfigure its voting configuration, which is exactly what the Voting Configuration Exclusions API is designed for.\n\nThe challenge is that this API normally requires a reachable master, but even without an elected master, Elasticsearch 7.x nodes can still accept local REST requests. So I should try calling the voting configuration exclusions endpoint directly on the remaining node to exclude the others from the quorum. I realize I should have called the voting config exclusions API before scaling down when the cluster still had a master. Since I've already scaled down, let me see if I can still invoke the API now to exclude those missing nodes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1600,"cache_read_input_tokens":43539,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1600},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1e168720-12b8-4366-8556-11e63d408ae8","uuid":"eb327b59-08e3-4042-af35-9bf04cd7fae0","request_id":"req_011CcMVNbwLMSTxvqFLLWR1a"}
