{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016kHSYycRmx2FGwiWdXWrgm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`unsafe-bootstrap` requires the Elasticsearch process to NOT be running. I need to:\n1. Kill the ES process in the container\n2. Run `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap`\n3. Start ES again\n\nBut this is a container - killing the main process would cause the pod to restart. However, the data is on the PVC, so on restart it will reload from disk.\n\nActually, the better approach here is:\n1. Kill the ES process (or stop it) in the container\n2. Run `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` \n3. Let the container restart (since killing the main process PID will cause the container to exit and restart)\nWhen the container restarts, it'll boot Elasticsearch again with the same configuration, but the cluster state will have been updated by `unsafe-bootstrap` to recognize it as a single-node cluster. So the sequence is to kill the Java process, run `unsafe-bootstrap` while ES is stopped, and let the pod restart to pick up the changes from the PVC.\n\nBut killing PID 13 will trigger a pod restart since it's the main entrypoint, which creates a race condition—I'd need to exec into the container and run `unsafe-bootstrap` before Elasticsearch fully starts up. A cleaner approach would be to stop the container entirely first, then run the bootstrap command without the restart happening in between. I'm realizing the race condition makes this approach fragile. Let me try a simpler path instead: I can modify the discovery settings in the Elasticsearch configuration to use single-node discovery mode, which would bypass the cluster formation issue entirely without needing to run unsafe-bootstrap at all.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":826,"cache_read_input_tokens":47901,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens"