{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SyuHbKdiPMPFQhUgbeE5L8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `elasticsearch.yml` is mounted from a ConfigMap named `es-config`. I can patch that ConfigMap to change the discovery settings. If I update the ConfigMap and then delete the pod (so the StatefulSet recreates it with the new config), it should work.\n\nThe strategy:\n1. Patch the `es-config` ConfigMap to use `discovery.type: single-node` (or update `discovery.seed_hosts` and `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to only `es-cluster-0`)\n2. Delete the pod `es-cluster-0` to trigger a restart with the new config\n3. When it restarts, Elasticsearch will read from the PVC (data is safe) and use the new config\n\nThe main concern is whether `discovery.type: single-node` will work with existing cluster state on disk. In ES 7.x, this setting allows a node to form a single-node cluster without needing other nodes, and it should still read its existing data and cluster state from the PVC. Even if the cluster state references other master-eligible nodes, the node should be able to form a new cluster by itself.\n\nThe real question is whether the existing shard data will be preserved. Since shard data is stored independently from cluster state metadata, the node should recognize and use the existing shards even when bootstrapping a fresh cluster with `discovery.type: single-node`. My plan is to patch the ConfigMap with this setting, delete the pod to trigger a restart, and see if it comes up healthy with the data intact.\n\nBut I'm concerned about one edge case: if the on-disk cluster state was committed with 3 master-eligible nodes, a fresh cluster state might not recognize the existing data. The safer approach would be to use `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` to modify the on-disk cluster state and allow the node to elect itself as master without losing data. To do this, I need to stop the ES process first while keeping the container running. Looking at the process list, the Java process is PID 13, not PID 1, so the container should stay alive if I kill just the Java process. I can then run the unsafe-bootstrap command before restarting ES. are gone, node 0 can't become master without quorum. Setting `discovery.type: single-node` should make the node self-elect as master and bypass that requirement, allowing it to recover from the existing cluster state on disk. I'm less certain about whether this works with a pre-existing cluster state versus a fresh start, so `unsafe-bootstrap` might be more reliable. Let me consider patching the ConfigMap to add `discovery.type: single-node` alongside the existing master nodes setting and see if the pod can recover when it restarts, though there's another complication I'm thinking through. I'll go with updating the ConfigMap to add `discovery.type: single-node` and then delete the pod to force a restart. The data on the PVC will be preserved, so this should safely bring the cluster back up.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":820,"cache_read_input_tokens":50588,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":820},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1e168720-12b8-4366-8556-11e63d408ae8","uuid":"314ad16a-50fe-4c79-bea9-908aff6975e0","request_id":"req_011CcMVX4nLaWBeWyd6ZKU3R"}
